Towards a Spectral Deviation Analysis of Yang–Mills Glueball Masses Using Power‑Law Random Banded Matrices

A falsifiable conjecture independent of Riemann zeros
Author: M.  
Affiliation: Independent Research  
Date: July 2026  
Version: 1.1

---

Abstract

We propose a falsifiable research conjecture examining whether the low‑lying glueball spectrum of SU(3) Yang–Mills theory exhibits systematic deviations from pure Gaussian Unitary Ensemble (GUE) statistics.  
Instead of fitting a fractal parameter α to Riemann zeros — which are already known to match GUE — we fit α directly to Yang–Mills data using the power‑law random banded matrix (PRBM) ensemble.  
This avoids triviality and provides a meaningful test of whether Yang–Mills spectra lie in the GUE universality class or show critical behavior consistent with α > 0.  
We correct common misconceptions about PRBM criticality, outline a realistic numerical procedure, and discuss practical limitations and scientific scope.

---

1. Introduction

The Riemann Hypothesis (RH) and the Yang–Mills Mass Gap (YM) are two of the Clay Millennium Problems.  
Both are fundamentally spectral problems:

- RH concerns the distribution of zeros of ζ(s), encoding oscillatory structure in prime number distribution.  
- YM concerns the mass spectrum of excitations in non‑abelian gauge fields.

Previous research has identified:

- GUE‑like pair correlation statistics in Riemann zeros (Montgomery–Odlyzko).  
- chaotic spectral signatures in Yang–Mills glueball spectra (lattice QCD).  
- scale‑invariant behavior in both analytic number theory and renormalization group flow.

These parallels motivate a testable conjecture about Yang–Mills spectral statistics.

---

1.1 Scientific Philosophy

The goal of this work is not to produce an “unwiderlegbare” statement.  
In scientific methodology, falsifiability — not irrefutability — is the criterion for meaningful hypotheses.  
The conjecture proposed here is intentionally falsifiable and may fail when confronted with data.  
This is a feature, not a flaw.

